it extended from southern uzbekistan and tajikistan , north of the amu darya ( oxus ) in the north west to pakistan and northern india , as far as mathura in the south east ( the rabatak inscription even claims he held pataliputra and sri champa ) , and his territory also included kashmir , where there was a town kanishkapur , named after him not far from the baramula pass and which still contains the base of a large stupa .

asian history : in the 1st century kanishka ruled a chunk of central asia from what 's now peshawar in this country

